    {
      "text": "High Bandwidth Memory was engineered to break the memory wall. Instead of placing chips on a separate circuit board connected by narrow traces, HBM stacks multiple DRAM dies vertically — connected by microscopic copper pillars called Through-Silicon Vias — then places them millimeters from the processor on a silicon interposer. The result: a 1,024-bit-wide bus delivering 1.2 terabytes per second. That is twenty times the bandwidth of DDR5.",
      "speaker": "Analyst",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
