    {
      "text": "Every GPU generation doubles the hunger. NVIDIA's H100 carried 80 gigabytes of HBM3. The H200 pushed to 141 gigabytes. The Blackwell B200 demands 192 gigabytes. The upcoming Rubin will need 288 gigabytes of HBM4 per chip. The brutal math: manufacturing one gigabyte of HBM consumes four times the silicon wafer area of standard DRAM. AI data centers are eating the world's semiconductor supply.",
