    {
      "text": "The deeper you look, the more fragile the architecture appears. Manufacturing HBM requires stacking up to 16 dies — a process where each bonding step compounds failure risk multiplicatively. Overall HBM yield is roughly 65 percent; for 16-layer HBM4, it drops to 50 to 60 percent. Nearly half of all production is discarded before it ships. And there is a second bottleneck: silicon interposer packaging, done almost exclusively through TSMC's CoWoS process, is equally constrained. The entire supply chain runs through Korea and Taiwan.",
      "speaker": "Analyst",
